<div id="review_198856939" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/198856939" />
    <a title="Connie G" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5364077-connie-g"><img alt="Connie G" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1307502493p2/5364077.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/198856939?book_show_action=true">Nov 18, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Connie G" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Connie G" href="/user/show/5364077-connie-g">Connie G</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5364077-connie-g?shelf=south-america">south-america</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5364077-connie-g?shelf=classic">classic</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5364077-connie-g?shelf=peru">peru</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer198856939" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer148958966979639750">The first sentence of this novella grabs our attention: &quot;On Friday noon, July the twentieth, 1714, the finest bridge in all Peru broke and precipitated five travelers into the gulf below.&quot; Brother Juniper was a witness to the terrible event and wondered why these five people were the victims. Was it fate or divine intervention?<br/><br/>For six years Brother Juniper studied the lives of these five people looking for patterns in their lives, or reasons that their deaths might be part of God&apos;s plan. The nar</span>
  <span id="freeText148958966979639750" style="display:none">The first sentence of this novella grabs our attention: "On Friday noon, July the twentieth, 1714, the finest bridge in all Peru broke and precipitated five travelers into the gulf below." Brother Juniper was a witness to the terrible event and wondered why these five people were the victims. Was it fate or divine intervention?<br /><br />For six years Brother Juniper studied the lives of these five people looking for patterns in their lives, or reasons that their deaths might be part of God's plan. The narrator claims to know even more about the five victims and the people important to them. The common theme running through their lives, and extending into the future, is love in many forms. "There is a land of the living and a land of the dead and the bridge is love, the only survival, the only meaning." Readers who like literary fiction should enjoy this Pulitzer Prize winner.</span>
  <a data-text-id="148958966979639750" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


